sigma_3(6) = 252 is the ONLY sigma_3 value that equals C(10,k) for any k!
  And C(10,5) = 252 is the middle binomial coefficient of row 10 = V(Petersen)

======================================================================
3. sigma_3(30) — THE E8 COXETER NUMBER
======================================================================

sigma_3(30) = sigma_3(h(E8)):

  Divisors of 30: [1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 15, 30]
  Number of divisors: 8 = rank(E8) = 2^3

  1^3 = 1
  2^3 = 8
  3^3 = 27
  5^3 = 125
  6^3 = 216
  10^3 = 1000
  15^3 = 3375
  30^3 = 27000

  sigma_3(30) = sum = 31752

  31752 = ?
    / 2    / 2    / 2    / 3    / 3    / 3    / 3    / 7    / 7

  a(30) = 240 * sigma_3(30) = 240 * 31752 = 7620480
  = the number of E8 lattice vectors at norm 30 = h(E8)

======================================================================
4. WEIGHT-4 EISENSTEIN SERIES E_4 AND E_6
======================================================================

E_4(q) = Theta_{E8}(q) (by Jacobi's theorem)
E_6(q) = 1 - 504*sum sigma_5(n)*q^n

Eisenstein series comparison:
   n    E_4 coeff    E_6 coeff        ratio
--------------------------------------------------
   0            1            1            1
   1          240         -504       -10/21
   2         2160       -16632       -10/77
   3         6720      -122976      -10/183
   4        17520      -532728   -730/22197
   5        30240     -1575504      -10/521
   6        60480     -4058208      -10/671
   7        82560     -8471232   -430/44121
   8       140400    -17047800     -26/3157
   9       181680    -29883672 -7570/1245153
  10       272160    -51991632     -30/5731

Leading coefficients:
  E_4: 240 = #roots(E8)
  E_6: -504 = -504
  504 = 7*72 = H_forb_1 * sigma(30)
      = 7*72 = 504
  504/240 = 21/10 = 21/10 = H_forb_2/V(Petersen)

======================================================================
5. MODULAR DISCRIMINANT AND TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================

The modular discriminant: Delta = (E_4^3 - E_6^2) / 1728

  1728 = 12^3 = h(E6)^3 = h(F4)^3
       = KEY1^6 * KEY2^3
       = (KEY1*KEY2)^3 * KEY1^3 = h(G2)^3 * KEY1^3

  1728 = 2^6 * 3^3 = KEY1^6 * KEY2^3
  In the tournament recurrence a = A*2^n + B*3^n:
  1728 appears when A*2^6 + B*3^3 = A*64 + B*27 = 1728
  One solution: A=27=KEY2^3, B=0: 27*64 = 1728 ✓
  So 1728 = KEY2^3 * KEY1^6 (pure tournament recurrence)

j-invariant: j = E_4^3 / Delta = 1728*E_4^3/(E_4^3 - E_6^2)
  j = q^{-1} + 744 + 196884q + ...
  744 = 8*93 = rank(E8) * 93
  744 = 24*31 = |BT|*(h(E8)+1)
  744 = 744
  93 = 3*31 = KEY2*(h(E8)+1)

  196884 = 196883 + 1 (Monster moonshine: dim(V_nat) + 1)
  196883 = 47 * 59 * 71
  These primes: 47, 59, 71 are ALL primes
  47 = 48-1 = |BO|-1
  59 = prime
  71 = 72-1 = sigma(30)-1

======================================================================
6. JACOBI THETA AND TOURNAMENT RECURRENCE
======================================================================

The four Jacobi theta functions at the nome q:
  theta_2(q) = 2*sum q^{(n+1/2)^2}
  theta_3(q) = sum q^{n^2}
  theta_4(q) = sum (-1)^n q^{n^2}

Key identity: theta_3^8 = Theta_{E8}
(because E8 is the lattice of 8-dimensional theta functions)

Also: theta_2^4 + theta_4^4 = theta_3^4 (Jacobi!)
This is a CUBIC relation in the 4th powers — analogous to the
tournament recurrence which is a LINEAR relation in 2^n and 3^n.

theta_3(q)^k counts representations as sum of k squares:
  theta_3^1: r_1(n) = #{n = a^2}
  theta_3^2: r_2(n) = #{n = a^2+b^2} (Gauss circle)
  theta_3^4: r_4(n) = 8*sigma_1(n) for odd n (Jacobi)
  theta_3^8: r_8(n) = 16*sigma_3(n) = a(n)/15

r_8(n) — representations as sum of 8 squares:
  r_8( 1) =       16 = 16 *      1
  r_8( 2) =      112 = 16 *      7
  r_8( 3) =      448 = 16 *     28
  r_8( 4) =     1136 = 16 *     71
  r_8( 5) =     2016 = 16 *    126
  r_8( 6) =     3136 = 16 *    196
  r_8( 7) =     5504 = 16 *    344
  r_8( 8) =     9328 = 16 *    583
  r_8( 9) =    12112 = 16 *    757
  r_8(10) =    14112 = 16 *    882

For E8 lattice vectors (which are DIFFERENT from r_8 for Z^8):
  E8 norm-n count = 240*sigma_3(n) for n >= 1
  Ratio: 240/16 = 15 = C(h(G2), KEY1) = C(6,2)
  The E8 lattice has 15 = C(6,2) times more vectors than Z^8!

======================================================================
7. EISENSTEIN PRIMES AND THE TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================

Eisenstein integers Z[omega] where omega = e^{2pi*i/3}:
  omega^2 + omega + 1 = 0  (this IS Phi_3(omega) = 0!)

The tournament polynomial z^2-5z+6 over Z[omega]:
  At z=omega: omega^2 - 5*omega + 6 = (-omega-1) - 5*omega + 6 = -6*omega + 5
  At z=omega^2: omega^4 - 5*omega^2 + 6 = omega - 5*(-omega-1) + 6 = 6*omega + 11

Eisenstein norms of f evaluated at 3rd roots of unity:
  N(f(omega)) = N(5 - 6*omega) = 25 + 30 + 36 = 91
  = 91 = 7*13 = H_forb_1 * (h(F4)+1)
  = Phi_3(2) * Phi_3(3) = Phi_3(KEY1) * Phi_3(KEY2)

  N(f(omega^2)) = N(11 + 6*omega) = 121 - 66 + 36 = 91
  = 91 = same! (conjugate symmetry)

  91 = 7*13 = Phi_3(2)*Phi_3(3)
  This is the norm of f(z) at primitive cube roots!
  The NORM factors into products of cyclotomic values at KEY1 and KEY2.

For comparison, over Gaussian integers Z[i]:
  f(i) = 5 - 5i, N(f(i)) = 50 = 2*25 = KEY1*KEY1^4
  f(-i) = 5 + 5i, N(f(-i)) = 50
  50 = 2*5^2 = KEY1*(KEY1+KEY2)^2

======================================================================
8. THE MODULAR GROUP AND (2,3)
======================================================================

The modular group PSL(2,Z) = Z/2 * Z/3
(free product of cyclic groups of order KEY1 and KEY2!)

Generators: S: z -> -1/z (order 2 = KEY1)
            T: z -> z+1 (infinite order)
            ST has order 3 = KEY2

This means:
  PSL(2,Z) is the MOST FUNDAMENTAL (2,3)-object in all of mathematics.
  It is literally Z/KEY1 * Z/KEY2.

The fundamental domain has:
  Vertices at i, rho=e^(2pi*i/3), oo
  Angles: pi/KEY2 at rho, pi/KEY1 at i
  Hyperbolic area = pi/3 = pi/KEY2

Finite quotients of PSL(2,Z):
  PSL(2,2) = S_3, order 6 = h(G2)
  PSL(2,3) = A_4, order 12 = h(E6)
  PSL(2,5) = A_5, order 60 = |BI|/2
  PSL(2,7) = GL(3,2), order 168 = H_forb_1*|BT|

  |PSL(2,p)| = p(p-1)(p+1)/2 for prime p:
  |PSL(2, 2)| =      3
  |PSL(2, 3)| =     12 = h(E6) = h(F4)
  |PSL(2, 5)| =     60 = |BI|/2 = |A5|
  |PSL(2, 7)| =    168 = H_forb_1 * |BT| = rank(E8)*H_forb_2
  |PSL(2,11)| =    660 = ...
  |PSL(2,13)| =   1092 = 12*91 = h(E6)*Phi3(2)*Phi3(3)

|PSL(2,5)|/|PSL(2,3)| = 60/12 = 5 = KEY1+KEY2
|PSL(2,7)|/|PSL(2,5)| = 168/60 = 14/5
|PSL(2,3)|/|PSL(2,2)| = 12/6 = 2 = KEY1

